<LegalPage
  title="Privacy"
  eyebrow="Privacy · Last updated 10 July 2026"
  description="Somnary's privacy policy. We collect as little as possible: no data selling, no ad-tracking, and most of the site works without collecting anything that identifies you."
  lastUpdated="10 July 2026"
>
  <p class="lead">
    Somnary is built to need as little of your data as possible. This policy explains what we
    collect, why, and your rights. It’s written to align with the Australian Privacy Act 1988
    (and the Australian Privacy Principles) and, for visitors in the EU/UK, the GDPR.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>The short version:</strong> we don’t sell your data, we don’t run ad-tracking, and
    most of the site works without collecting anything that identifies you.
  </p>

  <h2>1. What we collect</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Newsletter (the dispatch):</strong> the dispatch newsletter isn’t publishing yet, but
      you can leave your email to be told when it launches. If you do, we store just that email
      address (in our database, hosted by Supabase — see “sharing” below), only to send you a note
      when the dispatch starts. Nothing else, no spam, and you can ask us to remove it any time.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Claim / label submissions:</strong> if you send us a sleep claim or a product label
      to check, we store what you submit (and your email only if you choose to add one) to help us
      decide what to research and to run the correction process. These are also stored in our
      Supabase database. Please don’t include personal health details — we don’t need them and ask
      you not to send them.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Analytics:</strong> we currently run no analytics: no third-party scripts, no
      cookies, no cross-site tracking, and no profile of you. If we add analytics later, it will
      be a privacy-respecting, cookieless tool (such as Plausible or Fathom) that measures only
      aggregate traffic, and we’ll update this policy before turning it on.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Search queries:</strong> sitewide search isn’t live yet. When it is, searches you
      run may be logged in aggregate, anonymised form to help us decide what to research and
      cover next. We won’t tie searches to your identity.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Community reports (when launched):</strong> these are anonymous by design: no
      name, no email, no account. Don’t include anything in a report that could identify you; we
      don’t want it and don’t store it.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Corrections / emails:</strong> if you email us, we keep your message and address to
      reply and to track the correction.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>The on-page assistant (“ask this page”):</strong> when you send a question to the
      optional assistant, the text of your question and the reviewed content of the page you’re on
      are sent to Google (the Gemini API) to generate the answer. We don’t attach your name, email,
      or an account (we don’t have one for you), and we don’t log your questions to build a profile
      of you. Google processes the request as our AI provider under its API terms. Because your
      question leaves our servers to reach Google, please don’t type anything into the assistant
      that identifies you or that you consider sensitive. The feature is optional: every page and
      its sources work fully without it.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>2. What we don’t do</h2>
  <p>
    No selling or renting of personal data. No advertising networks. No affiliate or vendor
    tracking pixels. No selling of search or interest data. Ever. It’s core to what Somnary is.
  </p>

  <h2>3. Why we can use your data (legal bases, for GDPR readers)</h2>
  <p>
    Newsletter: your consent. Anonymised analytics/search: our legitimate interest in running and
    improving the site. Emails: to respond to you.
  </p>

  <h2>4. Cookies</h2>
  <p>
    The site runs without tracking cookies, and we don’t currently set any non-essential cookies.
    If that ever changes for EU/UK visitors, we’ll add a consent banner before turning any such
    cookie on.
  </p>

  <h2>5. Sharing</h2>
  <p>
    We share data with the service providers that run the site for us: our host, Vercel;
    Supabase, which stores the email addresses and claim/label submissions described above (its
    servers are the database behind those two forms); and — only when you use the optional on-page
    assistant — Google, which processes your question and the page content through its Gemini API to
    generate the answer. If we add an email-sending tool (for the dispatch) or analytics, we’ll name
    them here too. Each is bound to handle data for us alone. We may disclose information if required
    by law.
  </p>

  <h2>6. Retention</h2>
  <p>
    Newsletter emails until you ask us to remove you (before launch, that removal is manual, by
    email); claim/label submissions for as long as they inform our research and the correction log;
    emails for as long as needed to handle your query; analytics in aggregate only.
  </p>

  <h2>7. Your rights</h2>
  <p>
    You can ask us to access, correct, or delete the personal data we hold about you (essentially
    just your email, if you’ve subscribed or written to us), and you can unsubscribe at any time.
    EU/UK readers also have GDPR rights including objection and portability. To exercise any of
    these, email <a href="mailto:sammymoz@gmail.com">sammymoz@gmail.com</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>8. Data location</h2>
  <p>
    Our service providers may store data outside Australia. Our host, Vercel, and our database
    provider, Supabase, operate globally and may process data in the United States, and Google (the
    Gemini API, used only for the on-page assistant) may likewise process your question in the
    United States. We choose providers with appropriate safeguards.
  </p>

  <h2>9. Children</h2>
  <p>
    The site isn’t directed at children, and we don’t knowingly collect their data.
  </p>

  <h2>10. Complaints</h2>
  <p>
    If you’re in Australia and think we’ve mishandled your data, you can complain to us first at
    <a href="mailto:sammymoz@gmail.com">sammymoz@gmail.com</a>, and then to the Office of the
    Australian Information Commissioner (OAIC). EU/UK readers may complain to their local
    data-protection authority.
  </p>

  <h2>11. Changes</h2>
  <p>We’ll update the “last updated” date when this policy changes.</p>
</LegalPage>
